BiocGF: interfacing to Geneformer with R

Vincent J. Carey, stvjc at channing.harvard.edu

July 15, 2024

Source: vignettes/BiocGF.Rmd
BiocGF.Rmd

Introduction

Geneformer is described in a Nature paper entitled Transfer learning enables predictions in network biology Theodoris et al. [2023]. The abstract concludes: “Overall, Geneformer represents a pretrained deep learning model from which fine-tuning towards a broad range of downstream applications can be pursued to accelerate discovery of key network regulators and candidate therapeutic targets.”

Software resources related to the model are available at huggingface.co.

A preprint with critical content is Kedzierska et al. Kedzierska et al. [2023]. This package collects tools and information related to both of these papers.

Package resources

Programming for the analyses presented in the papers is exclusively in python. We use basilisk to collect specified versions of all Pypi-resident dependencies. We also include a snapshot of the Geneformer software modules with BiocGF.

Exploring the model

The Huggingface model card for Geneformer indicates that the model includes 10.3 million parameters. Using the safetensors module we can see the tensors of weights. get_gf_safetensors retrieves an image of model weights distributed in the huggingface repository for Geneformer.

library(BiocGF)
pa = get_gf_safetensors()
td = tempdir()
unzip(pa, exdir=td)
nwts_safet(file.path(td, "GF_safetensors", "model.safetensors"))
## [1] 10290770
st = get_safet() # not standard, hands live python ref
oo = st$safe_open(file.path(td, "GF_safetensors", "model.safetensors"), "pt")
mk = oo$keys()
length(mk)
## [1] 107
head(sapply(mk, function(z) oo$get_tensor(z)$shape))

## torch.Size([256])

## torch.Size([256])

## torch.Size([1, 2048])

A benchmark dataset

The Kedzierska paper includes a figshare link to a loom file representing quantifications of single-cell RNA-seq analyses of pancreas tissue. This in turn refers to the integration benchmarking paper of Luecken et al. Luecken et al. [2022], including the remark:

We reprocessed the following public datasets for our integration tasks: pancreas
GSE81076, GSE85241, GSE86469, GSE84133, GSE81608 (Gene Expression
Omnibus (GEO)) and E-MTAB-5061 (ArrayExpress)...

This code chunk uses basilisk to hand back a python reference to the loom representation of this dataset provided by Kedzierska et al at figshare.
This can be converted to SingleCellExperiment in the chunk, before handing back to R.

library(BiocGF)
panc_path = get_panc_loom_path()
proc = basilisk::basiliskStart(BiocGF:::gfenv)
pancloom = basilisk::basiliskRun(proc, function() {
 anndata::read_loom(panc_path)
})
basilisk::basiliskStop(proc)
pancloom
## AnnData object with n_obs × n_vars = 16382 × 16388
##     obs: 'adata_order', 'batch', 'celltype', 'n_counts', 'n_genes', 'n_genes_by_counts', 'obs_names', 'size_factors', 'tech', 'total_counts'
##     var: 'ensembl_id', 'gene_symbols', 'has_ensembl_match', 'mean_counts', 'n_cells', 'n_cells_by_counts', 'pct_dropout_by_counts', 'total_counts', 'var_names'
##     layers: 'counts'

This representation of the data is terse. There is no metadata to discriminate donor or source (e.g., the GSE or MTAB elements noted above).

Tokenizing the loom RNA-seq content

The following call is time-consuming and is not evaluated.

tt = gf_tokenize_loom( panc_path )

A serialized version of the tokenization output is available for this dataset.

cur = getwd()
td = tempdir()
setwd(td)
pa = get_panc_tok_path()
unzip(pa)  # destination = "."
ds = getgf() # get python module
ref = ds$load_from_disk("panc_hfds/tbyr.dataset")
print(ref)
## Dataset({
##     features: ['input_ids', 'length'],
##     num_rows: 16382
## })
setwd(cur)
